The Ummahaat, an organ of the Muslim Students Society of Nigeria (MSSN), Lagos State Area Unit has held its annual Reportorial Conference. The conference, themed “Revamped Normalcy” was held at Yusuf Grillo Hall at the Yaba College of Technology (YABATECH) in Lagos. The guest speaker, Fadhila Odubanjo, urged Muslim women to do away with the archaic way of doing things and embrace change. “Change is constant, we need to change the way we organize our programmes and activities, the manner of relations and also employ the use of a project charter to calculate risks, budget and end result of our programmes,” she said.   ‘Ekiti, Osun polls litmus test for 2023…     826 Plateau pilgrims set for Saudi Arabia     Hospital laments N44m monthly diesel expenditure   According to her, COVID-19 has opened the eyes of the world to a new normal. “Leaders ought to be more professional and embrace dynamism, for example, programmes do not have to be physical anymore. I believe after the conference, we will be able to have a revamped normalcy in doing things,” she said. Ummahaat Coordinator Marufah Adeyinka, stated that the annual Ummahaat reportorial conference was held to give account of what has been done in the past year and discuss ways of improvement. “We want to tell leaders of each area council that we cannot keep doing things the same way and expect a different result, hence the theme Revamped Normalcy. It was meant to address the need for change, so that our successors can learn from it and improve too”.